 why the task of perfecting pregnancies now takes up a woman’s entire reproductive life, from menarche to menopause. Miranda R. Waggoner shows how the zero trimester rose alongside shifts in medical and public health priorities, contentious reproductive politics, and the changing realities of women’s lives in the twenty-first century. Waggoner argues that the emergence of the zero trimester is not simply related to medical and health concerns; it also reflects the power of culture and social ideologies to shape both population health imperatives and women’s bodily experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aHealth risk assessment. 0aPregnancyxComplicationsy21st century. 0aPregnancyxComplications. 0aPublic health. 0aReproductive healthy21st century. 0aReproductive health. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienexHistoryy21st century. 0aWomenxHealth and hygieney21st century. 0aWomenxHealth and hygiene. 0aWomen's health servicesxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy21st century. 0aWomen's health servicesxPolitical aspectsy21st century. 0aWomen's health servicesxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  a21st century reproduction.  aamerican womens health.  abetter birth.  abetter prenatal.  adisciplining womens bodies.  agender studies.  ahealthy pregnancy.  ahealthy reproduction.  amaternity.  amedical care prior to pregnancy.  apolitics of reproductions.  apolitics of womens health.  apublic health.  areproduction in the us.  areproductive freedom.  areproductive health.  areproductive politics.  awomens bodies.  awomens health and hygiene.  awomens health.  awomens issues.  awomens studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028806540